Healthcare Analysis¶

 * NIDDK (National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases) research creates knowledge about and treatments for the most chronic, costly, and consequential diseases.
 * The dataset used in this project is originally from NIDDK. The objective is to predict whether or not a patient has diabetes, based on certain diagnostic measurements included in the dataset.
 * Build a model to accurately predict whether the patients in the dataset have diabetes or not.

From the descriptive Analysis,

  • Dataset have 768 rows and 9 columns which contains zero nan values.
  • Pregnancies, Glucose, Blood Pressure, SkinThickness, Insulin, BMI, DiabetesPedigreeFunction, Age are feature variable.
  • Outcome is the Target variable contains 1 and 0 denoting the patient have diabetes or not.
  • Patients had minimum of 0 and maximum of 16 Preganancies.
  • Features like Glucose, Blood Pressure, SkinThickness, Insulin, BMI have minimum value of 0 which doesn't makes sense. Because the mentioned features should have some particular range of values.

From the graph, it is clear that the data is imbalanced. Outcome Variable is biased towards zero value. This may affect the model and leads to Type 2 Error. Since the domain is healthcare, True Negatives are really dangerous compared to False positive. So planned to use SMOTE method to oversampling of data when building the model.

Thoughts on building Models:

  • From the above analysis it is observed that data is mostly numerical and variables are depending on target somewhat linearly. Hence Logistic Regression, Support Vector Vlassifier and Random Forest are expected to work fine.
  • Also Building the models with other classification techniques such as Naive Bayes, Decision Tree Classifier and Compare all the models with KNN.
  • Will build models without oversampling data to show the difference why oversampling is important for this model and how it reduces the Type 2 Error.
  • To validate the models, train test split is used to test the trained model with test dataset.
  • Will Interpret the accuracy using confusion matrix, classification matrix, ROC Curve and AUC Score.
  • The model which gives high accuracy and high AUC score(less True Negatives) considered to be the good model.

Random Forest Model(res), Linear Regression Model(res) and Support Vector Classifier rbf Model shows better results than all Models and AUC score is almost equal for this three models. In choosing best, both the Linear Regression Model(res) and Support Vector Classifier rbf Model gives more False Positives. And also Support Vector Classifier rbf Model gives the least True Negatives. Since it is Healthcare domain to predict the disease, True Negatives are very risky. So we can't give up with SVM rbf Model.

As Overall, Random Forest Model(res) and Support Vector Classifier rbf Model are the best for this data.
